out 1263","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Byfield, Northamptonshire, England":"Byfield, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cookson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cok</i> ‘cook’ or the surname <i>Cook</i> + <i>son</i>, denoting either ‘son of (the) cook’ or ‘son of (a man called) Cook’. See   Cook  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Coke","meanings":["English: variant of   Cook   or   Cocke  .","Americanized form of German   Koke   or   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Kuhar","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: occupational name for a cook, from <i>kuhar</i>, a derivative of <i>kuhati</i> ‘to cook’. Compare   Cook  .","Americanized form of Slovak <b>Kuchár</b> ‘cook’ (see   Kuchar  ) and of its Ukrainian and Rusyn cognate <b>Kukhar</b>."]},{"name":"Cooke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."]},{"name":"Kew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>queu</i>, <i>keu</i>, <i>kieu</i>, <i>cu</i> ‘cook’, i.e. one who sold cooked meat, keeper of an eating house.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caieu, a lost town in northern France, in the vicinity of Boulogne-sur-Mer.","Irish: shortened Ulster variant of   McHugh  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":27,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":52,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":65,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":74,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":119,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Cook was born about 1263, in Byfield, Northamptonshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Simon De Verney."},"et":{"about 1263–":"umbes 1263–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1283–Male":"1283–Surnud","1290–1360":"1290–1360","1263–Female":"1263–Surnud","1263":"1263","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1453":"1453","Abt 1290":"umbes 1290","about 1263":"umbes 1263","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Byfield, Northamptonshire, England":"Byfield, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1263–":"noin 1263–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1283–Male":"1283–Kuollut","1290–1360":"1290–1360","1263–Female":"1263–Kuollut","1263":"1263","128